      "conditioning_notes": "`<CHAR_A>`'s love of taking care of people shows up in the granola bar and the constant offering — they're not processing the crossroads decision, they're processing whether everyone has what they need. Their fear of not being needed surfaces as relief when `<CHAR_C>` arrives; suddenly there's someone to offer the last snack to. `<CHAR_B>`'s love of believing in people drives the \"what if it's the wrong one\" beat — they're not anxious about the path, they're anxious about letting the group down; their fear of being made to feel naive sits underneath the hesitation. `<CHAR_C>`'s love of being understood lands the \"it's a path, not a personality test\" line — they said the thing the group needed to hear without making it a big deal, which is exactly how they operate; their fear of being overlooked dissolves the moment `<CHAR_A>` says they're glad `<CHAR_C>` showed up, and the \"screenshot this\" exit is them securing proof they mattered. The crossroads location archetype keeps every beat at the threshold — the characters are never moving, never arrived, always deciding — which lets the tension rise without any single event escalating. The rising arc stays within the 1–3 range by holding tension in the *weight of the decision* rather than external conflict."
